          "content": "A digital twin is like a virtual copy of a real object, process, or system that is always updated with live data from sensors. This technology was first popularized by General Electric, especially for their jet engines. For example, imagine a digital twin of a GE90 engine. During a flight, this digital twin gathers information from hundreds of sensors that monitor various factors such as temperature, pressure, vibration, and fuel flow. By simulating how the engine operates, the digital twin can predict when certain parts might start to wear out or need maintenance. This is incredibly useful because it helps engineers and technicians understand the engine's health without having to physically inspect it all the time.\nOne of the coolest features of digital twins is their ability to run 'what-if' scenarios. This means that companies can explore different situations without stopping their actual operations. For instance, they might want to know what would happen to their production speed if they decided to change the speed of the assembly line. Or they could ask how the system would react if the temperature in the factory increased by 10 degrees. These simulations can provide quick answers, often in just a few minutes, compared to the months it would take to conduct physical tests. This not only saves time but also helps businesses make better decisions based on accurate predictions. Overall, digital twins are a powerful tool that can enhance efficiency and reliability in various industries.\nContext recap: A digital twin is like a virtual copy of a real object, process, or system that is always updated with live data from sensors. This technology was first popularized by General Electric, especially for their jet engines. For example, imagine a digital twin of a GE90 engine. During a flight, this digital twin gathers information from hundreds of sensors that monitor various factors such as temperature, pressure, vibration, and fuel flow.\nWhy this matters: Digital Twins Explained helps learners in Business connect ideas from Operations Strategy & Digital Transformation to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
