          "id": "operations-management-401-l06-c1",
          "title": "From Linear to Circular",
          "content": "In our daily lives, we often follow a straightforward pattern known as the linear economy. This means we take resources from the Earth, create products, and then dispose of them when we no longer need them. Unfortunately, this method is not sustainable for our planet. Experts predict that by the year 2050, we will require the resources of three entire planets to meet our current consumption levels! To address this pressing issue, we can transition to a concept called the circular economy. This innovative approach encourages us to keep materials in use for as long as possible, rather than simply throwing them away. Instead of discarding items, we can focus on reusing, repairing, remanufacturing, and recycling them. In the circular economy, products are designed to be easily disassembled, which makes it simpler to recover materials for reuse. Additionally, businesses are evolving their models; instead of merely selling products, they might offer services. For example, instead of selling lightbulbs, a company might provide lighting as a service. This shift not only helps reduce waste but also allows us to enjoy the products we love while actively contributing to the protection of our planet. By embracing the circular economy, we can create a more sustainable future for ourselves and generations to come.\nContext recap: In our daily lives, we often follow a straightforward pattern known as the linear economy. This means we take resources from the Earth, create products, and then dispose of them when we no longer need them. Unfortunately, this method is not sustainable for our planet. Experts predict that by the year 2050, we will require the resources of three entire planets to meet our current consumption levels!\nWhy this matters: From Linear to Circular helps learners in Business connect ideas from Operations Strategy & Digital Transformation to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
